<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does built-in refrigerator repair cost in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Our diagnostic fee is $89, waived when you approve the repair. Built-in refrigerator repairs typically run $200–$700 depending on the component and brand. Thermostat, fan motor, or evaporator defrost repair is toward the lower end. Compressor replacement on a Sub-Zero, Thermador, or Miele built-in is $600–$1,200+. Given that quality built-in refrigerators cost $6,000–$20,000+, repair is almost always the right decision at these price points."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What makes repairing a built-in refrigerator different from a freestanding model?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Three key differences: (1) Access — built-in refrigerators ventilate through the front grille, not the rear. They're installed flush with cabinetry and cannot be pulled out for rear access. All service must be done from the front or through the interior. (2) Components — built-in models use commercial-grade compressors, more sophisticated control systems, and in Sub-Zero's case, dual separate compressor systems. (3) Panel-ready models — refrigerators with custom cabinetry panels require careful handling to avoid damaging the cabinetry during service."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My Sub-Zero refrigerator is not cooling — what should I check first?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Check the vacuum condenser first. Sub-Zero built-ins have a vacuum condenser that requires cleaning every 12 months — when it's clogged with dust and debris, the compressor overheats and the refrigerator loses cooling capacity. The condenser is accessed through the front grille at the bottom. If cleaning the condenser doesn't restore cooling within 24 hours, call us — it may be a compressor, sealed system, or control board issue that requires diagnosis."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is it worth repairing a Sub-Zero or Miele built-in refrigerator vs replacing it?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Almost always yes for quality built-in refrigerators. Sub-Zero, Wolf, Thermador, and Miele built-ins are designed and built to last 20+ years with proper service. A $500 compressor repair on a $15,000 Sub-Zero is 3% of replacement cost. Even a $1,200 sealed system repair on an 18-year-old unit is almost always better than $15,000+ for a replacement. We'll give you the repair cost upfront so you can make the decision with full information — but for quality built-ins, repair is almost universally the right call."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you repair Sub-Zero, Wolf, Thermador, and Miele built-in refrigerators?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Sub-Zero, Wolf, Thermador, and Miele are the four most common luxury built-in refrigerator brands we service in Los Angeles. We also repair Gaggenau, GE Monogram, KitchenAid built-in, Dacor, and Viking built-in models. Parts sourced through luxury appliance specialty distributors."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is Sub-Zero's dual compressor system and why does it matter for repair?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Sub-Zero built-in refrigerators use two separate compressors — one dedicated to the refrigerator section and one to the freezer section. This is different from every other refrigerator brand which uses a single compressor for both. The benefit is independent temperature control and longer food preservation. For repair, it means diagnosing which compressor system has failed. If only the refrigerator section is warm while the freezer is fine (or vice versa), that pinpoints which compressor circuit to service."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

