<!-- BUILT-IN vs FREESTANDING -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02 — Why Built-In Repair Is Different</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Three reasons built-in refrigerator repair requires specific experience</h2>

    <div class="diff-grid">
      <div class="diff-card builtin">
        <h3>🔧 Built-In Refrigerator</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Front-ventilated — condenser and compressor accessible only from the front</li>
          <li>Flush installation — cannot be moved without disassembling the cabinetry interface</li>
          <li>Panel-ready models have custom cabinetry panels that must be handled carefully during service</li>
          <li>Commercial-grade compressors — longer life, different failure modes than residential</li>
          <li>Sub-Zero: dual compressor system — two independent sealed systems</li>
          <li>Miele/Gaggenau: European sealed system specs, specialty refrigerant handling</li>
          <li>More complex control systems — error codes, diagnostic modes, software updates</li>
          <li>Parts expensive but availability good through specialty distributors</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="diff-card free">
        <h3>📦 Freestanding Refrigerator</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Rear-ventilated — compressor and condenser accessible from the back</li>
          <li>Can be pulled away from the wall for full access</li>
          <li>Standard residential components — widely available parts</li>
          <li>Single compressor for both fresh food and freezer sections</li>
          <li>Simpler control systems on most models</li>
          <li>Lower replacement cost — repair vs. replace math is different</li>
          <li>LG, GE, Samsung, Whirlpool — standard residential service</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- DUAL COMPRESSOR -->
    <div class="dual-block">
      <div class="d-label">⚙️ Sub-Zero Dual Compressor — What It Means for Repair</div>
      <h3>Sub-Zero is the only residential refrigerator brand with two independent compressor systems</h3>
      <p>Every Sub-Zero built-in refrigerator has one compressor dedicated to the fresh food section and a separate compressor dedicated to the freezer section. This is fundamentally different from every other brand on the market, which uses a single compressor that cycles air between both sections.</p>
      <p>The benefit is independent temperature control and dramatically better food preservation — the sealed freezer air never mixes with the refrigerator air, eliminating freezer burn and extending fresh food life. Sub-Zero's dual compressor design is a primary reason these refrigerators last 20+ years when maintained.</p>
      <p>For repair, dual compressor means: if your refrigerator section is warm but the freezer is fine (or vice versa), that narrows the diagnosis immediately to one of the two compressor circuits. We diagnose both systems independently, which is why Sub-Zero repair requires a technician familiar with this specific architecture.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03 — Common Failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians diagnose most often in LA built-in refrigerators</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Not Cooling / Warm Temperatures</h3>
        <p>Check the condenser first (Sub-Zero and many other built-ins). If condenser is clean, it's likely the compressor, sealed system, or evaporator. On Sub-Zero: which section is warm? Refrigerator-only warm = refrigerator compressor. Freezer-only warm = freezer compressor. Both sections warm = control board or power issue. This differential diagnosis is only possible on Sub-Zero's dual compressor system.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Error Codes on Display</h3>
        <p>Modern built-in refrigerators (Sub-Zero, Miele, Thermador, Gaggenau) display error codes for specific faults — temperature sensor failure, door seal error, compressor fault, fan motor fault. We interpret these codes for the specific brand and model before touching any components. Many "error code" calls turn out to be sensor or control board issues rather than mechanical failures.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Ice Maker Not Producing</h3>
        <p>Built-in refrigerator ice makers fail for the same reasons as standard models — water inlet valve, ice maker module, temperature sensor — but access is different and parts are brand-specific. Sub-Zero ice makers are in the fresh food section (not the freezer), which is an unusual configuration. Miele and Thermador ice makers have different module designs from standard residential units.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Water Dispenser / Filter Issues</h3>
        <p>Water line freeze, failed water inlet valve, or a water filter that's overdue for replacement and restricting flow. Many LA built-in refrigerators have filtered water dispensers — the filter should be replaced every 6 months. A severely expired filter often causes low water pressure that's mistaken for a valve failure.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Compressor Noise / Vibration</h3>
        <p>Built-in refrigerators are designed to run quietly — any significant noise change is worth diagnosing. A grinding compressor sound indicates bearing wear. A clicking sound that repeats every few minutes is a compressor trying and failing to start (thermal overload cycling). A gurgling or hissing is usually normal refrigerant flow. We distinguish these on-site before recommending any compressor work.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Door Seal / Gasket Failure</h3>
        <p>A failed door gasket on a built-in refrigerator causes warm temperatures and excessive compressor cycling — the refrigerator works harder to maintain temperature because conditioned air is escaping. Panel-ready models with custom cabinetry panels have a different gasket system than standard stainless units. Gasket replacement requires careful removal of the door panel without damaging the finish.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- BRANDS -->
<section class="section">
